React Hooks – Complete Notes (with Examples & Interview Questions)
1. What are Hooks in React?

Hooks are special functions introduced in React v16.8 that allow functional components to use state, lifecycle methods, and other React features without writing class components.

Before Hooks, developers had to use class components to manage state and lifecycle methods.

Example (Before Hooks – Class Component)
class Counter extends React.Component {
  constructor(){
    super();
    this.state = {count:0};
  }

  render(){
    return(
      <button onClick={()=>this.setState({count:this.state.count+1})}>
        {this.state.count}
      </button>
    )
  }
}
Example (With Hooks – Functional Component)
import { useState } from "react";

function Counter(){
  const [count,setCount] = useState(0);

  return(
    <button onClick={()=>setCount(count+1)}>
      {count}
    </button>
  )
}
Rules of Hooks (Very Important for Interviews)

Only call Hooks at the top level

Only call Hooks inside React functions

Do not call Hooks inside loops, conditions, or nested functions.

Example ❌ Wrong

if(condition){
 useState()
}

Example ✅ Correct

const [count,setCount] = useState(0)
